Macedonians vote in referendum to change the country's name
On Sunday, the people of Macedonia voted in a referendum to decide whether its name will be changed to "Republical of North Macedonia", a movement which could resolve a decades-old dispute with Greece, which had blocked its efforts for membership in the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which has a province called Macedonia, thinks its northern neighbour's name constitutes a claim on its territory, and has vetoed its NATO and EU membership.
The two governments reached an agreement in June based on the proposed new name, but nationalist opponents argue that the change could compromise the ethnic identity of the majority Slavic of Macedonia's population.
President Gjorge Ivanov has indicated that he will not vote in the referendum, and a boycott campaign has cast doubt on whether voter turnout will reach the 50 per cent needed for the validity of the referendum.
The question on the referendum ballot sheet reads: "Are you for NATO and EU membership through acceptance of agreement with Greece?"
Supporters of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that for Macedonia, as one of the countries created by the dissolution of Yugoslavia, this is a price worth paying to achieve membership in structures such as the EU and NATO.
"I have come today to vote for the future of the country, for the young people of Macedonia, so that they can live free under the umbrella of the European Union, as this implies a safer life for all of us", 79-year-old Olivera Georgijevska said in Skopje.
Although the referendum has no binding powers, a sufficient number of MPs have indicated they will abide by the result of the vote to make it decisive.
The name change requires a two-thirds majority in parliament.
The state election commission said no irregularities had been reported until 1 pm.
However, voter turnout was only 16 per cent, compared to 34 per cent in the last parliamentary elections of 2016, where 66 per cent of registered voters cast their vote.
"I came to vote for the sake of my children, we have the country in Europe", said Jose Tanevski, 62, voters in the capital Skopje.
Macedonia's Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and son Dushko cast their vote in the referendum on changing the name of Macedonia, which would pave the way for the country's membership in NATO and the European Union, in Strumica, Macedonia, September 30, 2018.
In front of parliament in Skopje, 54-year-old Vladimir Kavardarkov was preparing a minor scene and was placing chairs in front of tents set up by referendum boycotters.
"We are for NATO and the EU, but we want to join the head up, not by entering the back door", Kavadarkov said.
"Our country is poor, but we have dignity.
If they do not want us by the name of Macedonia, we can address other states such as China and Russia and become part of Euro-Asian integration".
Prime Minister Zaev says NATO membership will bring much needed investment for Macedonia, which has an unemployment rate of over 20 per cent.
"I think the overwhelming majority will be the pro, as more than 80 per cent of our citizens are pro-EU and NATO", Zaev said after casting his vote.
He said a positive result would "confirm our future".
According to a survey published last Monday by the Institute of Macedonia for Political Research, about 30 per cent to 43 per cent of voters would participate in the referendum - a figure below the necessary level of turnout.
Another poll conducted by Macedonian television Telma found that 57 per cent of the participants planned to vote on Sunday.
Of these, 70 per cent indicated they would vote in pros.
For a successful referendum, the turnout rate should be 50 per cent plus one vote.
The failure of the referendum would give the first strong hit to the pro-Western government's policy, since it came to power in May last year.
