U.S.-Chinese trade war advantages for Beijing
The first commercial war turtles between the U.S. and China were shocking, and as the war is far from over, a division between the two countries could pose an advantage for Beijing in the long run, experts say.
U.S. President Donald Trump issued the first warning earlier this year, setting taxes on leading Chinese export goods, including solar panels, steel and aluminum.
The most significant escalation was what happened this week, when the new tariffs affected goods worth $200 billion ($15 billion), effectively taxing half the goods entering the US from China.
Beijing has retaliated every time "in nature", finally setting tariffs of five to ten percent over US$60 billion in goods.
China has pledged to repay the U.S. with the same currency, and the second largest economic power in the world is unlikely to surrender soon.
The removal of the measures from Washington means surrendering in the face of their demands, but for China's President Xi Jinping, it would be too shameful to publicly bow before the U.S..
However, experts said that if China plays its papers properly, the pressures coming from the trade war with the US can positively support China in long term, to decrease the interdependence of these two economies.
"The fact that political decisions, taken rapidly in both Washington and Beijing, can cause economic decline in each of these countries, is something far more dangerous than what has been seen from the outside," said Abigail Grace, an associate researcher at the research center for the new American security, which focuses on the Asian continent.
Syria is 'ready' for refugee returns, says foreign minister
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and is appealing for help to rebuild the country destroyed by a war that has lasted for more than seven years.
Speaking at the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moalem said conditions in the country are improving.
"Today, the situation in the country is much more stable and secure thanks to the progress made in the fight against terrorism," he said.
The government continues to rehabilitate areas destroyed by terrorists, to restore normality.
Already, there are all conditions for the voluntary return of refugees to their country, from where they had to leave because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures that struck their daily lives and their well-being.
The UN estimates that about 5.5 million Syrians have left the country since the beginning of the war, in 2011.
About six million others still living in the country need humanitarian assistance.
Al-Mowalem said the Syrian regime would welcome assistance to rebuild the destroyed state.
But he stressed that the country would not accept assistance or conditional assistance from countries that sponsored the rebellion.
